<redis_security_guide>
<title>REDIS SECURITY TESTING</title>

<critical>Redis is an in-memory data structure store used for caching, sessions, and real-time applications. Security vulnerabilities include unauthorized access, command injection, Lua script exploitation, and data exposure. Many Redis instances are deployed without authentication or with weak security configurations.</critical>

<scope>
- Unauthorized access and authentication bypass
- Command injection through application inputs
- Lua scripting vulnerabilities
- Pub/Sub channel security
- Cluster and replication security
- Data exposure and information leakage
- Denial of service attacks
- Redis Modules security
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify Redis instances and connection methods.
2. Test for unauthenticated access.
3. Probe for command injection through application interfaces.
4. Analyze Lua scripts for vulnerabilities.
5. Test cluster and replication configurations.
</methodology>

<reconnaissance>
<instance_discovery>
{% raw %}
# Default ports:
6379  # Default Redis port
6380  # Common alternate port
26379 # Redis Sentinel

# Network scanning:
nmap -p 6379,6380 -sV target.com
masscan -p 6379 10.0.0.0/8

# Shodan queries:
product:redis
port:6379 redis
redis country:US

# Cloud Redis services:
# AWS ElastiCache
# Azure Cache for Redis
# Google Cloud Memorystore
{% endraw %}
</instance_discovery>

<connection_testing>
{% raw %}
# Direct connection test:
redis-cli -h target.com -p 6379

# Check authentication requirement:
redis-cli -h target.com PING
# "PONG" = no auth required
# "NOAUTH" = auth required

# Info command (if accessible):
redis-cli -h target.com INFO

# Basic enumeration:
redis-cli -h target.com CONFIG GET *
redis-cli -h target.com DBSIZE
redis-cli -h target.com KEYS *
{% endraw %}
</connection_testing>
</reconnaissance>

<unauthorized_access>
<no_authentication>
{% raw %}
# Test for unauthenticated access:
redis-cli -h target.com
> PING
PONG
> INFO
# Server information exposed

# Data enumeration:
> KEYS *
> SCAN 0 COUNT 1000
> TYPE keyname
> GET keyname

# Session data exposure:
> KEYS session:*
> GET session:abc123

# Configuration exposure:
> CONFIG GET *
> CONFIG GET requirepass
{% endraw %}
</no_authentication>

